NATO launched its first coordinated operation after a deep-sea communications cable in the Baltic Sea was severed amid sabotage suspicions. The incident affects critical European infrastructure. Investigations seek to identify culprits, potentially including Russia, while the alliance bolsters defenses around undersea assets.

US forces captured a third Venezuelan oil tanker in the Indian Ocean, weeks after it left Venezuelan waters. President Trump stated the US has received 80 million barrels total from such seizures. Venezuela loses revenue from sanctioned oil exports, with further captures possible. In Sudan, unidentified drones struck the Kordofan region's gold and oil sites, killing dozens and displacing thousands. This escalates fighting between the Sudanese army and Rapid Support Forces along a new frontline, stalling peace efforts. Separately in eastern Congo, Rwanda-backed rebels overran troops and sparked gunfire and shelling in Goma, a safe-haven city sheltering over 1 million displaced people according to the UN. Aid operations face strain.

Palestinians crossed a military zone on foot to return to northern Gaza after Israel opened the bisecting area following a hostage deal. Hundreds of thousands previously evacuated now begin rebuilding amid ongoing fighting. German Chancellor Friedrich Merz arrived in Beijing for economic talks, discussing German firms' market access, China's ties to Moscow, and EU relations. Louvre director Laurence des Cars resigned after an October crown jewels heist, labor strikes, and scandals at the museum that draws 9 million visitors annually. The International Criminal Court charged former Philippine President Rodrigo Duterte over his drug war that killed thousands since 2016. Sri Lanka arrested ex-intelligence chief Suresh Sallay for aiding the 2019 Easter Sunday bombings that killed nearly 300. A Seoul court convicted shaman Jeon Seong-bae of bribery linked to ex-First Lady Kim Keon-hee. President Trump delivered a 100-minute State of the Union address, the longest in decades.
